														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4865532">
									

<p>Seeking Greenlights: yes</p>
<p>Page type: SCP article</p>
<p>Elevator pitch: This SCP is a Stuffed Pelican that causes any individual who touches it, or is too close to begin to hallucinate that every living being is a pelican, as well as hearing the song &quot;Pelicans we&quot; by Cosmo Sheldrake at high volumes to the point that it hurts the ears and causes headaches. Sometimes also causes blurry vision. This SCP is to be only handled by an individual wearing a sealed HAZMAT suit and is kept in a sealed glass container with a danger line on the floor marking the range of effect.</p>
<p>Central Narrative: This SCP is marked as Safe and/or Explained as it was discovered that it was manufactured in the 1960s and was held in possession of a prolific drug user who primarily used inhalable hallucinogens. The drugs and the anomalous energy caused by the drug use infused into the pelican causing it's effects. It has not been neutralized or destroyed, and research is going towards neutralization.</p>
<p>Hook/Attention Grabber: Not many &quot;explained&quot; SCPs are in effect currently (at least that I'm aware of, there are too many to be fully aware of all of them now) and it uses a historical period where drugs were common. There is still an anomalous nature that is common in SCP articles, so it works well with fitting in with the rest of them as well as being it's own thing.</p>
<p>Additional notes: The actual idea is inspired by the song itself, so I decided it should be included into the SCP itself. The song itself sounds like a drug trip, and is considered creepy by some of my friends, so it seemed like a good idea to state it as a hallucinogenic SCP. Then it made more sense to have a pelican involved as the actual object, and a stuffed animal seemed like a fair play. It's normally a rather insignificant and everyday object that is changed by it's anomalous properties. I'm also looking for critiques to make the proposal/other proposals in the future better, not just the greenlight to make it an article.</p>

							</div>

								
					
